{
  "text": " Look at this chimpanzee. It's using a stick to eat termites. And this one is using a leaf to scoop water. This was huge because for a long time we thought that it was only us humans that made and used tools, so much so that we actually defined ourselves by it. Until Jane Goodall, carefully studied chimps in Tanzania in 1960, quietly observing them, and doing unconventional things like naming them and noting their personalities. She discovered that they didn't just use tools, they made them too. They didn't just eat plants, but also meat. They formed strong family bonds and fought over land. She revealed that they were much more complex than we ever thought, teaching us so much more about our closest relative and about ourselves. So thank you, Jane Goodall. We'll really miss you.",
